      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Why F-Words Matter in Scrabble</h2>
      <p>At 4 points per tile, F is one of the higher-value consonants in the game. With only two F tiles in the entire bag, drawing one is relatively uncommon — which means opponents won't easily block positions that work well for F-words. The letter pairs naturally with high-value companions like X, Z, and J to create explosive scoring combinations.</p>
      <p>F-words shine in the short-word department. Three-letter plays like FIZ (15 pts), FEZ (15 pts), FOX (13 pts), FIX (13 pts), and FAX (13 pts) deliver outstanding point-per-tile ratios. When these land on premium squares, they can produce 30-45 point turns from just three tiles — leaving you four tiles for your next rack.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Strategy for Playing F-Words</h2>
      <p>F rewards aggressive play. Here are the key tactics for maximising your F-word scoring:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Pair F with X or Z:</strong> Words like FOX, FIX, FAX, FEZ, and FIZ combine two premium consonants. Landing the X or Z on a bonus square while F provides the structure is devastating.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Use FF for double value:</strong> Words like AFFIX (18 pts), BAFFLED, DAFFODIL, and OFFHAND contain double-F. The 8 base points from two F tiles alone give these words a scoring floor.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Front-hook existing words:</strong> F makes excellent hooks — LOCK → FLOCK, LOWER → FLOWER, RIGHT → FRIGHT. These create two scoring words simultaneously.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Target TLS with short F-words:</strong> FIZ on a triple-letter square under the Z scores 45 points. FOX on TLS under the X scores 37. Always scan for these setups.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>FJORD is a J-dumper:</strong> If you're stuck with J and no vowel-friendly position, FJORD (16 pts) uses J without requiring a vowel adjacent to it — a rare and valuable pattern.</span></li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Essential Short F-Words</h2>
      <p>These compact F-words should be in every competitive player's memory. They fit tight board positions and deliver high points-per-tile ratios:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Two-letter:</strong> FA (5 pts) — valid and useful for parallel plays alongside existing words</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Three-letter power words:</strong> FIZ (15), FEZ (15), FOX (13), FIX (13), FAX (13) — five words averaging 14 points each</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Four-letter plays:</strong> FLUX (14), FLEX (14), FLAX (14), FAUX (14) — all use X for consistent 14-point returns</span></li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">When to Hold vs Play Your F</h2>
      <p>F is scarce — only two tiles exist. If you've already seen one F played, the remaining tile becomes even more valuable because opponents can't easily counter F-based positions. Hold your F when the board has accessible premium squares that could benefit from a FIZ or FOX play next turn.</p>
      <p>Play your F immediately when you have a premium-square opportunity now, when your rack is consonant-heavy and you need the 4 points flowing, or when holding it would prevent you from playing a bingo (all 7 tiles for the 50-point bonus).</p>

